<TITLE> France arrests Rwandan genocide suspect </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - French police have arrested a former Rwandan army officer suspected of taking part in the country's 1994 genocide, a French prosecutor said on Wednesday. Marcel Bivugabagabo, 53, was arrested in the southern city of Toulouse on Tuesday, prosecutor Richard Bometon said. "His arrest at his home took place without incident. The file of the man was transmitted to us by Interpol. His identity has been checked," Bometon said, adding authorities would decide on the man's possible extradition. A Rwandan official said the accused faced charges of genocide and crimes against humanity which he allegedly committed in the former Northern Ruhengeri province where he worked as an army commander. "We issued an indictment for him in September last year and we were told by Interpol last evening that he's in their custody," said Rwandan prosecution spokesman Jean Bosco Mutangana in Kigali. Rwanda wants the fugitive to be extradited home to face trial, which is unlikely since the tiny nation has no extradition treaty with France. Rwanda cut diplomatic relations in November after a French judge called for Rwandan President Paul Kagame to stand trial over the death of his predecessor in April 1994 -- an event that unleashed the country's genocide, in which some 800,000 ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus were slaughtered. French President Nicolas Sarkozy said after a meeting with Kagame during an EU-Africa summit last month that France had begun to normalise relations with Rwanda. The Rwandan official said France was home to nine fugitives appearing on its indictment list, which was updated last ye
